"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:11.4.1.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">11.4.1.2</span> Palm</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">טֶפַח</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tefach)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:26\">1KI 7:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:5\">2CH 4:5</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">טֹפַח</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tofach)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod25:25\">EXO 25:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod37:12\">EXO 37:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:5\">EZK 40:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:43\">EZK 40:43</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek43:13\">EZK 43:13</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">טַפְחָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tafchah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps39:6\">PSA 39:6</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">The <em>tefach</em> /<em>tofach</em> is the width of the hand at the base of the fingers, not including the thumb.</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod25:25\">EXO 25:25</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod37:12\">EXO 37:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:26\">1KI 7:26</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:5\">2CH 4:5</a>: In many languages it will be possible to express these words as the Hebrew does, as the width of a hand. Otherwise a measurement such as “8 centimeters” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"French Common Language Version (Bible en français courant)\">FRCL</abbr>) or “3 inches” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>) will do. For some reason <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr> have “three inches” in the Exodus references but “four inches” in 1 Kings and 2 Chronicles.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:5\">EZK 40:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek43:13\">EZK 43:13</a>: Here the cubit is said to be longer by one <em>tofach</em>. This is the measure used throughout chapters 40–48 of Ezekiel. The shorter cubit actually measured about 45 centimeters (18 inches), and this longer one would have been 53 centimeters (21 inches). Some translations try to reflect the difference. Many, however, will prefer to use a rounded-off value of 50 centimeters (18 inches) for both.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps39:6\">PSA 39:6</a>: Here the word <em>tefach</em> (<em>tapchah</em>) is a symbolic figure indicating the shortness of life. This may be the basis for the statement of Jesus in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt6:27\">MAT 6:27</a>. See the discussion under <em>pēchus</em> below.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
